{{Infobox book | name = Art and Scholasticism | title_orig = Art et scolastique | translator = | image = Art and Scholasticism (French edition).jpg | caption = | author = [[Jacques Maritain]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = France | language = French | series = | subject = [[Aesthetics]] | published = 1920 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]] and [[Paperback]]) | pages = | isbn = 978-1599868479 | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Art and Scholasticism''''' ({{lang-fr|Art et scolastique}}) is a 1920 book by the philosopher [[Jacques Maritain]], his major contribution to [[aesthetics]].<ref>[[#Hal05|Haldane 2005]]. p. 555.</ref> According to Gary Furnell, the work "was a key text that guided the work of writers such as [[Allen Tate]], [[Caroline Gordon]], Sally and [[Robert Fitzgerald]], [[François Mauriac|Francois Mauriac]], [[Thomas Merton]], [[John Howard Griffin]], [[Flannery O'Connor|Flannery O’Connor]] and [[T. S. Eliot|T.S. Eliot]]."<ref>[[#Fu15|Furnell 2015]]. p. 105.</ref> Maritain's Thomist-Aristotelian distinction between Art and Prudence was highly influential on the sculptor [[Eric Gill]], and were developed further in the seminal essay on theological aesthetics, entitled 'Art and Sacrament', by poet and painter [[David Jones (artist-poet)|David Jones]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Epoch and Artist|last=Jones|first=David|publisher=Faber & Faber|year=1955|isbn=978-0571242054|location=|pages=143-179}}</ref>
