[[File:Opera Dardanella ad p15.JPG|thumb|300px|Advertisement for a Dardanella performance, 1929]] '''Dardanella''' was a touring theatre company from the [[Dutch East Indies]] (modern-day Indonesia) established by Willy A. Piedro in 1926. Arising from a background of [[musical theatre]], the troupe focused on realistic stories, both adaptations of foreign works and original [[stage play]]s about life in the Indies. Starring Dewi Dja' and Tan Tjeng Bok, the troupe performed original works by Piedro and [[Andjar Asmara]]. Popular both in the Indies and abroad, Dardanella dissolved during an international tour after 1936. Several of its members later went into film.
==Background== In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, the theatre in the [[Dutch East Indies]] (modern-day Indonesia) generally emphasised music, with the dialogue being sung. These early performances were given different names depending on their type, such as ''[[bangsawan]]'' and ''komedi stambul''. In the mid-1920s companies in the country began adapting more European stylings, with an emphasis on spoken dialogue and a reduction in the amount of music used during the performance; troupes using this new format referred to the genre as ''[[toneel]]'', an adaptation of the Dutch word for theatre.{{sfn|Cohen|2003|pp=215–217}}{{sfn|Cohen|2006|p=338}}
==Career== [[File:Dr Samsi advertisement, Doenia Film October 1931 p14.jpg|thumb|300px|Advertisement for the premiere of ''Dr Samsi''; the play became Dardanella's most popular.]] Dardanella was established by Willy A. Piedro (born Willy Klimanoff), a [[Penang]]-born actor of Russian descent. His [[Native Indonesians|native]] wife, Dewi Dja' (also spelled Devi), joined as an actor; another early member was Tan Tjeng Bok, an ethnic Chinese ''[[keroncong]]'' singer who was known for his sword work, Ferry Kock, and [[Astaman]];{{sfn|JCG, Dardanella}}{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=14, 17}} many of these actors had been in other troupes before.{{sfn|Cohen|2006|p=348}} The troupe gave their first performance on 21&nbsp;June 1926 in [[Sidoarjo]], [[East Java]].{{sfn|JCG, Dardanella}} They were advertised as a ''toneel'' troupe to indicate their affinity for European stage traditions.{{sfn|Cohen|2006|p=338}}
Initially the troupe's works were written by Piedro. He adapted numerous [[Hollywood]] productions for the stage, including ''[[The Mark of Zorro (1920 film)|The Mark of Zorro]]'' (1920), ''[[The Three Musketeers (1921 film)|The Three Musketeers]]'' (1921), ''[[The Thief of Bagdad (1924 film)|The Thief of Bagdad]]'' (1924), and ''[[Don Q, Son of Zorro]]'' (1925). These adaptations generally starred Tan Tjeng Bok, who earned the nickname "[[Douglas Fairbanks]] of [[Java]]" ("{{lang|nl|Douglas Fairbanks van Java}}") for his work.{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=14, 17}} Piedro also wrote his own stage plays based on everyday life in the Indies (mostly in Java), such as ''Roos van Serang'', ''Fatima'', and ''North of Borneo''.{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=14, 17}}
The group attracted the theatre and film critic [[Andjar Asmara]] in November 1930; he left his publication ''Doenia Film'' to join as he believed the troupe dedicated to the betterment of the ''toneel'' as an art form and not only motivated by financial interests like the earlier ''stambul'' troupes.{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=6, 14, 20}} Andjar's wife [[Ratna Asmara|Ratna]] also joined.{{sfn|JCG, Dardanella}} He numerous wrote stage plays for the troupe, generally dealing with more serious and mature topics than Piedro; these were in part aimed at the growing [[intellectualism|intellectual]] native population.{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=6, 14, 20}}
Dardanella began losing its popularity in the early 1930s.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=24}} In 1936 Dardanella went to India to record a film adaptation of Andjar's ''Dr Samsi'', which followed a doctor who was blackmailed after an unscrupulous [[Indo people|Indo]] discovered he had an illegitimate child.{{sfn|Said|1982|pp=136–138}}{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=23}} This plan was not brought to fruition, and afterwards Piedro, Dja', and some thirty-odd players went to the United States via Egypt and Europe, soon disbanding.{{sfn|JCG, Dardanella}}{{sfn|Salim 2008, Dardanella}} Meanwhile, Andjar and Ratna Asmara returned to the Indies, establishing their own troupe named Bollero with [[Bachtiar Effendi]], who had joined Dardanella shortly before its dissolution.{{sfn|JCG, Dardanella}}{{sfn|Said|1982|p=138}}
In the 1940s numerous former Dardanella actors and personnel entered the film industry, including Andjar and Ratna Asmara,{{sfn|Said|1982|p=138}} as well as Ferry Kock and his wife Dewi Mada.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=204}} Several stage plays used by the troupe were also adapted to film, including ''[[Rentjong Atjeh]]'' (''Rencong of Aceh''; 1940),{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=210}} and ''[[Gadis Desa]]'' (''Maiden from the Village''; 1949).{{sfn|Encyclopedia of Jakarta, Andjar Asmara}}
==Style and reception== Their plays were presented in [[Malay language|Malay]] and often adapted works by other writers.{{sfn|JCG, Dardanella}} Some works, such as those by [[Victor Ido]], were translated from the original when adapted for stage.{{sfn|JCG, Dardanella}} Dardanella and its contemporary rival [[Miss Riboet's Orion]]&nbsp;– established a year before&nbsp;– were some of the first travelling troupes in the Indies to use original works; earlier ''[[bangsawan]]'' and ''stambul'' troupes had used broad outlines of foreign works.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=6}}{{sfn|Salim 2008, Dardanella}} The two were the most popular troupes from the Indies of their time.{{sfn|Salim 2008, Dardanella}}
A review in ''[[The Straits Times]]'' following a performance of ''The Worshippers of Papua'' in 1935 found the troupe's performances comparable to those of European theatrical acts and notes that large European audiences attended the shows. The reviewer described the show as "entertaining [audiences] in a way they had never been entertained before".{{sfn|The Straits Times 1935, Patrons}}
The Indonesian cultural critic Hairus Salim HS notes that Dardanella's use of Malay in a time of [[Indonesian National Awakening|increased nationalism]] worked to unite the different peoples of the [[Indonesian archipelago|archipelago]] with a single language; he also cites the diverse cultural background of its players as presenting a single but varied Indonesian identity.{{sfn|Salim 2008, Dardanella}}
