{{italic title}} '''''Sinfoni Melayu''''' (or ''Sinfoni Malaya'') is mentioned in the reference work ''Contemporary Composers''<ref>''Contemporary Composers'', ed. Brian Morton and Pamela Collins, Chicago and London: St. James Press, 1992 - {{ISBN|1-55862-085-0}}</ref> as a symphony composed by [[Anthony Burgess]] in 1956, when he was a teacher at [[Malay College Kuala Kangsar]]. In his book ''This Man and Music''<ref>Anthony Burgess, ''This Man And Music'', New York: McGraw-Hill, 1982 - {{ISBN|0-07-008964-7}}</ref> Burgess himself wrote:
: ''Sinfoni Melayu'', a three-movement symphony which tried to combine the musical elements of the country into a synthetic language which called on native drums and xylophones as well as instruments of the full Western orchestra. The last movement ended with a noble professional theme, rather [[Elgar]]ian, representing independence. Then, over a drum roll and before the final chord in C major, the audience was to rise and shout "[[Merdeka]]!"<ref>quoted in {{cite book | first = Mark | last = Crinson | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Modern Architecture and the End of Empire | publisher = Ashgate Publishing. | date = 2003 | location = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=JkNr4XZ-pYcC&pg=PA161&lpg=PA161 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0-7546-3510-4 | page = 228}} page 161</ref> In his ''Anthony Burgess Newsletter'' in 1999 [[Paul Phillips (conductor)|Paul Phillips]] called "''Sinfoni Malaya'' for orchestra and brass band” Burgess's second symphony, following Symphony No. 1, composed in 1935).<ref>{{cite web|first=Paul|last=Phillips|title=The Music of Anthony Burgess|url=http://bu.univ-angers.fr/EXTRANET/AnthonyBURGESS/NL1/NL1Music.html|work=Anthony Burgess Newsletter|publisher=The Anthony Burgess Centre, [[University of Angers]]|accessdate=8 June 2011|date=1999}}</ref>
The score of the symphony appears to have been lost, <ref>[http://www.anthonyburgess.org/anthony-burgess-his-life-work/music/1954-59.htm Music 1954-59], International Anthony Burgess Foundation {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100412072526/http://www.anthonyburgess.org/anthony-burgess-his-life-work/music/1954-59.htm |date=April 12, 2010 }}</ref> and there is no evidence that it was ever performed, so the only source for its existence is Burgess’s own testimony.
